sdp/verification/t-006@20260502t001347zc-verify.md:19:{"type":"tool_result","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:07:49.536Z","tool_id":"run_shell_command_1777687669374_0","status":"success","output":"diff --git a/ESCALATIONS.md b/ESCALATIONS.md\nindex c2d2d74..b4abff6 100644\n--- a/ESCALATIONS.md\n+++ b/ESCALATIONS.md\n@@ -58,6 +58,31 @@ curl -H \"X-Narrative-Auth: <long-random-token>\" \\\n   http://127.0.0.1:8765/health\n ```\n \n+## Network Allowlist\n+\n+Deniable Mac reaches the CypherClaw narrative API over Tailscale. If any\n+upstream firewall, router ACL, or cloud security group sits between Deniable\n+and CypherClaw, Deniable's current Tailscale IPv4 address must be added to\n+that allowlist or the narrative API calls will be silently dropped.\n+\n+Look up Deniable's current Tailscale IPv4 on the Deniable host:\n+\n+```bash\n+tailscale ip -4\n+# expected: a single 100.x.y.z address\n+```\n+\n+Add that address to the upstream allowlist:\n+\n+```\n+# Deniable Mac Tailscale IPv4 (replace placeholder with `tailscale ip -4` output)\n+<DENIABLE_TAILSCALE_IPV4>\n+```\n+\n+Re-run `tailscale ip -4` and update the allowlist whenever Deniable is\n+re-tailnetted or its node identity is reset, since the 100.x.y.z address can\n+change.\n+\n ## T-003@20260502T001347Z (2026-05-02T00:13:47Z)\n \n - **Reason:** Deploy-side narrative event store is not checked into this workspace"}
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:7:- `tests/test_narrative_api_health.py` (new file)
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:13:The `/health` endpoint returns HTTP 200 in all cases and includes all six required fields: `status`, `narrative_engine_importable`, `world_db_reachable`, `ollama_reachable`, `version`, `uptime_seconds`. The `status` field is `"ok"` when all three subsystem checks pass and `"degraded"` when any fail — matching the acceptance criteria exactly. The `uptime_seconds` field uses `time.monotonic()` anchored at app creation, which is correct. The world-db check exercises `list_world_events` with `limit=1`, confirming a real probe rather than a trivial sentinel.
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:17:Both the happy path (all checks pass → `"ok"`) and degraded path (any check fails → `"degraded"`) are tested with distinct test cases. The `BrokenEventStore` covers the exception path for `world_db_reachable`. The `_run_health_check` wrapper catches all exceptions and returns `False`, preventing any subsystem failure from propagating as a 500. One gap: there is no explicit test case where `narrative_engine_checker` raises an exception (as opposed to returning `False`). The behaviour is correct because `_run_health_check` handles it, but the test suite doesn't exercise that path for `narrative_engine_importable`. Minor.
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:21:The injectable `HealthChecker` protocol follows the same factory-injection pattern used for `memory_factory` and `event_store_factory`. Module-level helper functions (`_run_health_check`, `_default_narrative_engine_importable`, `_default_ollama_reachable`) are placed at module scope consistent with existing helpers such as `_normalize_domain_param`. The endpoint is unauthenticated, which is appropriate for health checks and consistent with typical FastAPI health endpoint conventions (no `require_auth` dependency injected).
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:25:- `/health` is intentionally unauthenticated — correct for a health endpoint that should be reachable by orchestrators without a token.
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:27:- Broad `except Exception` in `_run_health_check` is intentional and safe for a health aggregator; it prevents subsystem errors from leaking stack traces to callers.
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:36:The recurring failure mode flags concern `bootstrap_identity` not being invoked at startup before `FirstBootAnnouncer`. Confirmed: `create_app` in `narrative_api/app.py` does **not** call `bootstrap_identity`. However, this is a pre-existing systemic concern that predates T-009 and is outside this task's scope (health endpoint). The health endpoint itself does not depend on identity bootstrapping, and the task spec does not require startup identity wiring. This concern should be tracked as a separate task or added to T-010's startup wiring scope.
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:40:- [ ] No test case exercises `narrative_engine_checker` raising an exception (vs. returning False) — severity: **minor** (behaviour is correct via `_run_health_check`, just untested path)
sdp/verification/t-009@20260502t001347z-verify.md:47:1. Consider adding a test case: `narrative_engine_checker=lambda: (_ for _ in ()).throw(RuntimeError("import failed"))` (or a simple raising lambda) to explicitly cover the exception-suppression path in `_run_health_check` for the narrative engine check.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:17:1. **Unhealthy Ollama excluded from candidate list** — `QuotaMonitor._runtime_unavailable_agents()` calls `_refresh_local_provider_status()` on every `get_available_agents()` invocation. When `ollama_health.check_health()` returns `False` for all configured ports, the local provider is blocked and all agents mapped to it are added to the `blocked` set. These are excluded before both the healthy/warn filter and the fallback max-headroom selection.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:21:3. **Recovery when Ollama returns healthy** — Health is checked live (not cached between calls) in `_refresh_local_provider_status`. When any configured port returns healthy, `ollama` re-enters `fallback_candidates` and the standard selection path on the next call. No restart or manual intervention required.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:29:- All cloud providers also quota-paused AND Ollama unhealthy: `get_available_agents` returns `[]`, `_eligible_agents` returns `[]`, `select` raises `ValueError("no agents available for selection")` — correct escalation behavior.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:30:- Partial port recovery: any healthy port re-admits Ollama (documented tradeoff, see Consistency).
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:34:**Test coverage**: Two new targeted tests cover exclusion, fallback, and recovery paths at both the `QuotaMonitor` and `AgentSelector` levels. The `autouse` `_healthy_ollama` fixture correctly protects pre-existing tests from the new live health check.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:39:- Alert message updated to use runtime-specific language (`"runtime health recovers"` vs `"headroom recovers"`) for local providers — consistent with how quota vs runtime degradation is differentiated elsewhere.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:40:- The multi-port `any()` semantics (healthy if any port is up) is a deliberate design decision noted in ESCALATIONS.md: a single-socket outage does not block Ollama if another socket is healthy. This is consistent with the "best-effort local routing" philosophy and correctly documented.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:44:No security concerns. The `importlib.import_module("agent_selector")` call inside `_local_provider_ports` reuses an already-imported module from the same path — no new import-path attack surface beyond what existed before. No secrets, credentials, or user-controlled input flows into health check calls. `ollama_health.check_health(port)` takes an integer port, not a URL derived from external input.
sdp/verification/t-007@20260408t223256z-verify.md:51:- The renamed test (`test_ollama_never_excluded_from_selection` → `test_ollama_excluded_from_selection_when_unhealthy_and_recovers`) accurately describes the new behavior.
